The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Pact for Europe" announced by the European Commission is, to date, the first comprehensive plan for sustainable development decided by a major region of the planet.
It has therefore become a reference point for the entire world – a guide for the transition to a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is impressive: a sheer amount of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of related and interconnected subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
Sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined in accordance with objectives subject to a timeline, and programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net-zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that ends destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat highly processed industrial products, nor kill the land with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, critics will see public consultation announcements as mere empty talk.
But go talk to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced over a year of protests turning into riots, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted in unrest this autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality for their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately seeking how to organize or structure a public consultation, but in hindsight.
American adherents of neoliberalism will once again scoff, and claim that the "market" knows how to deal with climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that they are unusable, replaced by detours.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle now costs $8 billion, if not more, and is funded by billionaires, by large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and by interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
Solutions provided by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows a government as it should be, not a government subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense, not a narrow partisan one).
A mixed economy, which combines markets, the regulatory power of the state, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a socially democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and the collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, move toward a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flow of primary resources.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
Large oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public assistance.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like any other region of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small share of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly in the areas of new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, and the renewal of industrial equipment, among others. Funding will come from the private sector as well as from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts will have to be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
The European Union accounts for approximately 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to fully implement its Green Deal, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest emitter of CO2 (although its per capita emissions remain half of those of the United States).
China, alone, will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they face the dangers of the misguided cold war launched by America.
Hardline government figures and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially under pressure from the United States, since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead offers the latter a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish infrastructure, sustainable development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
The EU has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
